{"title_page": "Sumerian religion", "text_new": "{{multiple image|perrow=2|total_width=270|caption_align=center\n| align    = right\n| direction =vertical\n| header=Sumerian religion\n| image1   = Wall plaque from Ur 2500 BCE.jpg\n| caption1 = Wall plaque showing libations by devotees and a naked priest, to a seated god and a temple. [[Ur]], 2500 BCE.<ref>For a better image: [https://cdli.ucla.edu/dl/photo/P480697_d.jpg]</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Art of the First Cities: The Third Millennium B.C. from the Mediterranean to the Indus |date=2003 |publisher=Metropolitan Museum of Art |isbn=978-1-58839-043-1 |page=[https://archive.org/details/artoffirstcities0000unse/page/n152 74] |url=https://archive.org/details/artoffirstcities0000unse |url-access=registration |language=en}}</ref>\n| footer=\n}}\n{{Meso myth}}\n{{Ancient Near East mythology}}\n'''Sumerian religion''' was the [[religion]] practiced and adhered to by the people of [[Sumer]], the first [[literacy|literate]] civilization of [[ancient Mesopotamia]]. The Sumerians regarded their [[deity|divinities]] as responsible for all matters pertaining to the natural and social orders.<ref name=Kramer1963>{{cite book|last1=Kramer|first1=Samuel Noah|title=The Sumerians: Their History, Culture, and Character|date=1963|publisher=The Univ. of Chicago Press|location=|isbn=0-226-45238-7|url=https://archive.org/details/sumerianstheirhi00samu|url-access=registration}}</ref>{{rp|3\u20134}}\n \nBefore the beginning of kingship in Sumer, the city-states were effectively ruled by theocratic priests and religious officials. Later, this role was supplanted by kings, but priests continued to exert great influence on Sumerian society. In early times, Sumerian temples were simple, one-room structures, sometimes built on elevated platforms. Towards the end of Sumerian civilization, these temples developed into [[ziggurat]]s\u2014tall, pyramidal structures with sanctuaries at the tops.\n\nThe Sumerians believed that the God of Monkeys lived in Mhow. First, [[Nammu]], the primeval waters, gave birth to [[Anu|An]] (the sky) and [[Ki (goddess)|Ki]] (the earth), who mated together and produced a son named [[Enlil]]. Enlil separated heaven from earth and claimed the earth as his domain. Humans were believed to have been created by [[Enki]], the son of An and Nammu. [[Heaven]] was reserved exclusively for deities and, upon their deaths, all mortals' spirits, regardless of their behavior while alive, were believed to go to [[Kur]], a cold, dark cavern deep beneath the earth, which was ruled by the goddess [[Ereshkigal]]  and where the only food available was dry dust. In later times, Ereshkigal was believed to rule alongside her husband [[Nergal]], the god of death.\n\nThe major deities in the Sumerian pantheon included An, the god of the heavens, Enlil, the god of wind and storm, [[Enki]], the god of water and human culture, [[Ninhursag]], the goddess of fertility and the earth, [[Utu]], the god of the sun and justice, and his father [[Sin (mythology)|Nanna]], the god of the moon. During the [[Akkadian Empire|Akkadian Period]] and afterward, [[Inanna]], the goddess of sex, beauty, and warfare, was widely venerated across Sumer and appeared in many myths, including the famous story of her [[Inanna#Descent into the Underworld|descent into the Underworld]].\n\nSumerian religion heavily influenced [[Mesopotamian mythology|the religious beliefs of later Mesopotamian peoples]]; elements of it are retained in the mythologies and religions of the [[Hurrians]], [[Akkadian Empire|Akkadians]], [[Babylonians]], [[Assyria]]ns, and other Middle Eastern culture groups. Scholars of comparative mythology have noticed many parallels between the stories of the ancient Sumerians and those recorded later in the early parts of the [[Hebrew Bible]].\n\n==Worship==\n\n===Written cuneiform===\n[[File:Temple evolution in cuneiform (sound E).jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|Evolution of the word \"Temple\" ([[Sumerian language|Sumerian]]: \"[[\u00c9 (temple)|\u00c9]]\") in [[cuneiform]], from a 2500 BCE relief in [[Ur]], to Assyrian cuneiform circa 600 BCE.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Budge |first1=E. A. Wallis (Ernst Alfred Wallis) |title=A guide to the Babylonian and Assyrian antiquities |date=1922 |publisher=British Museum |page=[https://archive.org/details/guidetobabylonia00briiala/page/22 22] |url=https://archive.org/details/guidetobabylonia00briiala}}</ref>]]\nSumerian myths were passed down through the [[oral tradition]] until the invention of writing (the earliest myth discovered so far, the [[Epic of Gilgamesh]], is Sumerian and is written on a series of fractured clay tablets). Early Sumerian [[cuneiform]] was used primarily as a record-keeping tool; it was not until the late [[History of Sumer#Early Dynastic period|early dynastic period]] that religious writings first became prevalent as temple praise hymns<ref name=ETCSL>{{cite web|url=http://etcsl.orinst.ox.ac.uk/edition2/literature.php|title=Sumerian Literature|publisher=Electronic Text Corpus of Sumerian Literature|accessdate=2009-06-22}}</ref> and as a form of \"incantation\" called the ''nam-\u0161ub'' (prefix + \"to cast\").<ref name=Lexicon>{{cite web| url=http://www.sumerian.org/sumerian.pdf |title=The Sumerian Lexicon|publisher=John A. Halloran|accessdate=2009-06-23}}</ref> These tablets were also made of stone clay or stone, and they used a small pick to make the symbols.\n\n===Architecture===\n{{Main|Sumerian architecture}}\n[[File:Plaque_with_libation_scene_BM_120850.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Plaque with a libation scene. 2550-2250 BCE, [[Royal Cemetery at Ur]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Art of the First Cities: The Third Millennium B.C. from the Mediterranean to the Indus |date=2003 |publisher=Metropolitan Museum of Art |isbn=978-1-58839-043-1 |page=[https://archive.org/details/artoffirstcities0000unse/page/n153 75] |url=https://archive.org/details/artoffirstcities0000unse |url-access=registration |language=en}}</ref><ref>Found loose in soil at the cemetery {{cite book |last1=Hall |first1=H. R. (Harry Reginald) |last2=Woolley |first2=Leonard |last3=Legrain |first3=Leon |title=Ur excavations |date=1900 |publisher=Trustees of the Two Museums by the aid of a grant from the Carnegie Corporation of New York |page=525 |url=https://archive.org/details/urexcavations186385join/page/524/mode/2up/search/U.+7900}}</ref>]]\nIn the Sumerian city-states, temple complexes originally were small, elevated one-room structures. In the early dynastic period, temples developed raised terraces and multiple rooms. Toward the end of the Sumerian civilization, [[ziggurats]] became the preferred temple structure for Mesopotamian religious centers.<ref name=BYU>{{cite web| url=http://mi.byu.edu/publications/books/?bookid=21&chapid=112 |title=Inside a Sumerian Temple|publisher=The Neal A. Maxwell Institute for Religious Scholarship at Brigham Young University |accessdate=2009-06-22}}</ref>\nTemples served as cultural, religious, and political headquarters until approximately 2500 BC, with the rise of military kings known as [[Lugal|Lu-gal]]s (\u201cman\u201d + \u201cbig\u201d)<ref name=\"Lexicon\"/> after which time the political and military leadership was often housed in separate \"palace\" complexes.\n\n===Priesthood===\n[[File:Sumerian Worshiper.JPG|thumb|Statuette of a Sumerian worshipper from the [[Early Dynastic Period (Mesopotamia)|Early Dynastic Period]], ca. 2800-2300 BC]]\n\nUntil the advent of the lugals, Sumerian city states were under a virtually [[Theocracy|theocratic]] government controlled by various [[EN (cuneiform)|En]] or [[Ens\u00ed]], who served as the [[high priest]]s of the cults of the city gods. (Their female equivalents were known as [[NIN (cuneiform)|Nin]].) Priests were responsible for continuing the cultural and religious traditions of their city-state, and were viewed as mediators between humans and the cosmic and terrestrial forces. The priesthood resided full-time in temple complexes, and administered matters of state including the large [[irrigation| irrigation processes]] necessary for the civilization's survival.\n\n===Ceremony===\nDuring the [[Third Dynasty of Ur]], the Sumerian city-state of [[Lagash]] was said to have had sixty-two \"lamentation priests\" who were accompanied by 180 vocalists and instrumentalists.\n\n==Cosmology==\nThe Sumerians envisioned the universe as a closed dome surrounded by a primordial saltwater sea.<ref name=Firmament>{{cite web| url=http://faculty.gordon.edu/hu/bi/Ted_Hildebrandt/OTeSources/01-Genesis/Text/Articles-Books/Seely-Firmament-WTJ.pdf |title=The Firmament and the Water Above|publisher=Westminster Theological Journal 53 (1991), 232-233|accessdate=2010-02-20}}</ref> Underneath the terrestrial earth, which formed the base of the dome, existed an underworld and a freshwater ocean called the [[Aps\u00fb]]. The deity of the dome-shaped [[firmament]] was named [[An (god)|An]]; that of the earth was named [[Ki (goddess)|Ki]]. First the underground world was believed to be an extension of the goddess Ki, but later developed into the concept of [[Kur]]. The primordial saltwater sea was named [[Nammu]], who became known as [[Tiamat]] during and after the [[Third Dynasty of Ur|Sumerian Renaissance]].\n\n===Creation story===\n{{Main|Sumerian creation myth}}\n{{multiple image|perrow=2|total_width=450|caption_align=center\n| align    = right\n| direction =horizontal\n| header=Early religious relief (c.2700 BCE)\n| image1   = Carved figure feathers Louvre AO221.jpg\n| caption1 = \n| image2   = Tablet of the figure with feathers, circa 2700 BCE, Girsu, Sumer.jpg\n| footer=Carved figure with feathers. The king-priest, wearing a net skirt and a hat with leaves or feathers, stands before the door of a temple, symbolized by two great maces. The inscription mentions the god [[Ningirsu]]. [[Early Dynastic Period (Mesopotamia)|Early Dynastic Period]], circa 2700 BCE.<ref>{{cite web |title=Louvre Museum Official Website |url=http://cartelen.louvre.fr/cartelen/visite?srv=car_not_frame&idNotice=11372 |website=cartelen.louvre.fr}}</ref>\n}}\nThe main source of information about the Sumerian creation myth is the prologue to the epic poem ''[[Gilgamesh, Enkidu, and the Netherworld]]'',<ref name=Kramer1961/>{{rp|30\u201333}} which briefly describes the process of creation: originally, there was only [[Nammu]], the primeval sea.<ref name=Kramer1961/>{{rp|37\u201340}} Then, Nammu gave birth to [[Anu|An]], the sky, and [[Ki (goddess)|Ki]], the earth.<ref name=Kramer1961/>{{rp|37\u201340}} An and Ki mated with each other, causing Ki to give birth to [[Enlil]], the god of wind, rain, and storm.<ref name=Kramer1961/>{{rp|37\u201340}} Enlil separated An from Ki and carried off the earth as his domain, while An carried off the sky.<ref name=Kramer1961/>{{rp|37\u201341}}\n\n===Heaven===\n{{Main|Seven Heavens}}\nThe ancient Mesopotamians regarded the sky as a series of domes (usually three, but sometimes seven) covering the [[flat earth]].<ref name=Nemet1998>{{citation|last=Nemet-Nejat|first=Karen Rhea|authorlink=Karen Rhea Nemet-Nejat|date=1998|title=Daily Life in Ancient Mesopotamia|publisher=Greenwood|series=Daily Life|isbn=978-0313294976|url=https://archive.org/details/dailylifeinancie00neme}}</ref>{{rp|180}} Each dome was made of a different kind of precious stone.<ref name=Nemet1998/>{{rp|203}} The lowest dome of heaven was made of [[jasper]] and was the home of the [[star]]s.<ref name=Lambert2016>{{cite book|last1=Lambert|first1=W. G.|title=Ancient Mesopotamian Religion and Mythology: Selected Essays|date=2016|publisher=Mohr Siebeck|location=Tuebingen, Germany|editor1-last=George|editor1-first=A. R.|editor2-last=Oshima|editor2-first=T. M.|isbn=978-3-16-153674-8|series=Orientalische Religionen in der Antike|volume=15|page=118|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dTLWQddp8zwC&pg=PA118&dq=Heaven+in+Mesopotamian+religion&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjFwqeqx_DWAhVLzoMKHVuFArIQ6AEIKjAB#v=onepage&q=Heaven%20in%20Mesopotamian%20religion&f=false}}</ref> The middle dome of heaven was made of ''saggilmut'' stone and was the abode of the [[Igigi]].<ref name=Lambert2016/> The highest and outermost dome of heaven was made of ''lulud\u0101n\u012btu'' stone and was personified as [[Anu|An]], the god of the sky.<ref>{{citation|last=Stephens|first=Kathryn|title=An/Anu (god): Mesopotamian sky-god, one of the supreme deities; known as An in Sumerian and Anu in Akkadian|url=http://oracc.museum.upenn.edu/amgg/listofdeities/an/|website=Ancient Mesopotamian Gods and Goddesses|publisher=University of Pennsylvania Museum|date=2013}}</ref><ref name=Lambert2016/> The [[Astronomical object|celestial bodies]] were equated with specific deities as well.<ref name=Nemet1998/>{{rp|203}} The planet [[Venus]] was believed to be [[Inanna]], the goddess of love, sex, and war.<ref name=Black1992>{{citation|last=Black |first=Jeremy |first2=Anthony |last2=Green |title=Gods, Demons and Symbols of Ancient Mesopotamia: An Illustrated Dictionary |publisher=The British Museum Press|year=1992 |isbn= 0-7141-1705-6}}</ref>{{rp|108\u2013109}}<ref name=Nemet1998/>{{rp|203}} The [[sun]] was her brother [[Utu]], the god of justice,<ref name=Nemet1998/>{{rp|203}} and the [[moon]] was their father [[Sin (mythology)|Nanna]].<ref name=Nemet1998/>{{rp|203}} Ordinary mortals could not go to heaven because it was the abode of the gods alone.<ref name=\"Wright2000\">{{cite book|last1=Wright|first1=J. Edward|title=The Early History of Heaven|date=2000|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Oxford, England|isbn=0-19-513009-X|page=29|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lKvMeMorNBEC&pg=PA26&dq=Heaven+in+Mesopotamian+religion&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjFwqeqx_DWAhVLzoMKHVuFArIQ6AEIOzAE#v=onepage&q=Heaven%20in%20Mesopotamian%20religion&f=false}}</ref> Instead, after a person died, his or her soul went to [[Kur]] (later known as [[Irkalla]]), a dark shadowy [[underworld]], located deep below the surface of the earth.<ref name=\"Wright2000\"/><ref name=Choksi2014>{{citation|last=Choksi|first=M.|date=2014|title=Ancient Mesopotamian Beliefs in the Afterlife|url=http://www.ancient.eu/article/701/|website=Ancient History Encyclopedia|publisher=ancient.eu}}</ref>\n\n===Afterlife===\n{{main|Kur}}\n[[File:Dumuzi aux enfers.jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|Ancient Sumerian [[cylinder seal]] impression showing the god [[Dumuzid the Shepherd|Dumuzid]] being tortured in the [[Kur|Underworld]] by ''[[gallu|galla]]'' demons]]\n[[File:VAM - Rollsiegel 1.jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|Devotional scene, with Temple.]]\nThe [[Sumer]]ian afterlife was a dark, dreary cavern located deep below the ground,<ref name=Choksi2014/><ref>{{cite journal|last=Barret|first=C. E.|date=2007|title=Was dust their food and clay their bread?: Grave goods, the Mesopotamian afterlife, and the liminal role of Inana/I\u0161tar|journal=Journal of Ancient Near Eastern Religions|volume=7|issue=1|pages=7\u201365|location=Leiden, The Netherlands|publisher=Brill|url=http://booksandjournals.brillonline.com/content/journals/10.1163/156921207781375123|doi=10.1163/156921207781375123|issn=1569-2116}}</ref> where inhabitants were believed to continue \"a shadowy version of life on earth\".<ref name=Choksi2014/> This bleak domain was known as [[Kur]],<ref name=Black1992/>{{rp|114}} and was believed to be ruled by the goddess [[Ereshkigal]].<ref name=Choksi2014/><ref name=Nemet1998/>{{rp|184}} All souls went to the same afterlife,<ref name=Choksi2014/> and a person's actions during life had no effect on how the person would be treated in the world to come.<ref name=Choksi2014/>\n\nThe souls in Kur were believed to eat nothing but dry [[dust]]<ref name=Black1992/>{{rp|58}} and family members of the deceased would ritually pour [[libation]]s into the dead person's grave through a clay pipe, thereby allowing the dead to drink.<ref name=Black1992/>{{rp|58}} Nonetheless, funerary evidence indicates that some people believed that the goddess [[Inanna]], Ereshkigal's younger sister, had the power to award her devotees with special favors in the afterlife.<ref name=Choksi2014/> During the [[Third Dynasty of Ur]], it was believed that a person's treatment in the afterlife depended on how he or she was buried;<ref name=Black1992/>{{rp|58}} those that had been given sumptuous burials would be treated well,<ref name=Black1992/>{{rp|58}} but those who had been given poor burials would fare poorly.<ref name=Black1992/>{{rp|58}}\n\nThe entrance to Kur was believed to be located in the [[Zagros mountains]] in the far east.<ref name=Black1992/>{{rp|114}} It had seven gates, through which a soul needed to pass.<ref name=Choksi2014/> The god [[Neti (deity)|Neti]] was the gatekeeper.<ref name=Nemet1998/>{{rp|184}}<ref name=Black1992/>{{rp|86}} Ereshkigal's ''sukkal'', or messenger, was the god [[Namtar]].<ref name=Black1992/>{{rp|134}}<ref name=Nemet1998/>{{rp|184}} ''[[Gallu|Galla]]'' were a class of demons that were believed to reside in the underworld;<ref name=Black1992/>{{rp|85}} their primary purpose appears to have been to drag unfortunate mortals back to Kur.<ref name=Black1992/>{{rp|85}} They are frequently referenced in magical texts,<ref name=Black1992/>{{rp|85\u201386}} and some texts describe them as being seven in number.<ref name=Black1992/>{{rp|85\u201386}} Several extant poems describe the ''galla'' dragging the god [[Dumuzid the Shepherd|Dumuzid]] into the underworld.<ref name=Black1992/>{{rp|86}} The later Mesopotamians knew this underworld by its [[East Semitic]] name: [[Irkalla]]. During the [[Akkadian Empire|Akkadian Period]], Ereshkigal's role as the ruler of the underworld was assigned to [[Nergal]], the god of death.<ref name=Choksi2014/><ref name=Nemet1998/>{{rp|184}} The Akkadians attempted to harmonize this dual rulership of the underworld by making Nergal Ereshkigal's husband.<ref name=Choksi2014/>\n\n==Pantheon==\n{{see also|List of Mesopotamian deities}}\n\n===Development===\n[[File:Mu\u0161\u1e2bu\u0161\u0161u on a vase of Gudea, circa 2100 BCE.jpg|thumb|upright=0.5|The dragon [[Mu\u0161\u1e2bu\u0161\u0161u]] on a vase of [[Gudea]], circa 2100 BCE.]]\nIt is generally agreed that Sumerian [[civilization]] began at some point between c. 4500 and 4000 BC, but the earliest historical records only date to around 2900 BC.<ref>{{cite book| last=Bertman| first=Stephen| title=Handbook to life in ancient Mesopotamia| year=2003| publisher=Facts on File| isbn=978-0-8160-4346-0| url=https://archive.org/details/handbooktolifein00bert| url-access=registration|page=[https://archive.org/details/handbooktolifein00bert/page/143 143]}}</ref> The Sumerians originally practiced a [[polytheistic]] religion, with [[anthropomorphic]] [[deity|deities]] representing cosmic and terrestrial forces in their world.<ref name=Nemet1998/>{{rp|178\u2013179}} The earliest [[Sumerian literature]] of the third millennium BC identifies four primary deities: [[Anu|An]], [[Enlil]], [[Ninhursag]], and [[Enki]]. These early deities were believed to occasionally behave mischievously towards each other, but were generally viewed as being involved in co-operative creative ordering.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Sources of the Old Testament: A Guide to the Religious Thought of the Old Testament in Context|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EG4CYbEbOrwC&pg=PA29|accessdate=7 May 2013|date=18 May 2004|publisher=Continuum International Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-567-08463-7|pages=29\u2013}}</ref>\n\nDuring the middle of the third millennium BC, Sumerian society became more urbanized.<ref name=Nemet1998/>{{rp|178\u2013179}} As a result of this, Sumerian deities began to lose their original associations with nature and became the patrons of various cities.<ref name=Nemet1998/>{{rp|179}} Each Sumerian city-state had its own specific patron deity,<ref name=Nemet1998/>{{rp|179}} who was believed to protect the city and defend its interests.<ref name=Nemet1998/>{{rp|179}} Lists of large numbers of Sumerian deities have been found. Their order of importance and the relationships between the deities has been examined during the study of [[cuneiform]] tablets.<ref>{{cite book|title=God in Translation: Deities in Cross-cultural Discourse in the Biblical World|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yvWlC0kUlkYC&pg=PA42|accessdate=7 May 2013|year=2010|publisher=Wm. B. Eerdmans Publishing|isbn=978-0-8028-6433-8|pages=42\u2013}}</ref>\n\nDuring the late 2000s BC, the Sumerians were conquered by the [[Akkadian Empire|Akkadians]].<ref name=Nemet1998/>{{rp|179}} The Akkadians [[syncretism|syncretized]] their own gods with the Sumerian ones,<ref name=Nemet1998/>{{rp|179}} causing Sumerian religion to take on a Semitic coloration.<ref name=Nemet1998/>{{rp|179}} Male deities became dominant<ref name=Nemet1998/>{{rp|179}} and the gods completely lost their original associations with natural phenomena.<ref name=Nemet1998/>{{rp|179\u2013180}} People began to view the gods as living in a [[feudal society]] with [[class structure]].<ref name=Nemet1998/>{{rp|179\u2013181}} Powerful deities such as [[Enki]] and [[Inanna]] became seen as receiving their power from the chief god [[Enlil]].<ref name=Nemet1998/>{{rp|179\u2013180}}\n\n===Major deities===\n[[File:Ea (Babilonian) - EnKi (Sumerian).jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|Akkadian [[cylinder seal]] from sometime around 2300 BC or thereabouts depicting the deities [[Inanna]], [[Utu]], [[Enki]], and [[Isimud]]<ref name=Kramer1961/>{{rp|32\u201333}}]]\n\nThe majority of Sumerian deities belonged to a classification called the ''Anunna'' (\u201c[offspring] of [[An (mythology)|An]]\u201d), whereas seven deities, including Enlil and Inanna, belonged to a group of \u201cunderworld judges\" known as the ''[[Anunnaki]]'' (\u201c[offspring] of An\u201d + [[Ki (goddess)|Ki]]). During the [[Third Dynasty of Ur]], the Sumerian pantheon was said to include sixty times sixty (3600) deities.<ref name=Nemet1998/>{{rp|182}}\n\n[[Enlil]] was the god of air, wind, and storm.<ref name=Davidson2015>{{citation|last1=Coleman|first1=J. A.|last2=Davidson|first2=George|title=The Dictionary of Mythology: An A-Z of Themes, Legends, and Heroes|date=2015|publisher=Arcturus Publishing Limited|location=London, England|isbn=978-1-78404-478-7|page=108}}</ref>{{rp|108}} He was also the chief god of the Sumerian pantheon<ref name=Davidson2015 />{{rp|108}}<ref>{{citation|first=Samuel Noah|last=Kramer|title=The Sumerian Deluge Myth: Reviewed and Revised|journal=Anatolian Studies|volume=33|date=1983|jstor=3642699|publisher=British Institute at Ankara|doi=10.2307/3642699}}</ref>{{rp|115\u2013121}} and the patron deity of the city of [[Nippur]].<ref name=Schneider2011>{{citation|last=Schneider|first=Tammi J.|title=An Introduction to Ancient Mesopotamian Religion|publisher=William B. Eerdman's Publishing Company|location=Grand Rapids, Michigan|date=2011|isbn=978-0-8028-2959-7|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2HfU9gv0fXYC&pg=PA58}}</ref>{{rp|58}}<ref>{{citation|last=Hallo|first=William W.|article=Review: Enki and the Theology of Eridu|title=Journal of the American Oriental Society|volume=116|issue=2|date=1996}}</ref>{{rp|231\u2013234}} His primary consort was [[Ninlil]], the goddess of the south wind,<ref>{{citation|last1=Black|first1=Jeremy A.|last2=Cunningham|first2=Graham|last3=Robson|first3=Eleanor|title=The Literature of Ancient Sumer|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=a1W2mTtGVV4C&pg=PA106|date=2006|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-929633-0}}</ref>{{rp|106}} who was one of the matron deities of [[Nippur]] and was believed to reside in the same temple as Enlil.<ref name=Ninlil>{{cite web|url=http://etcsl.orinst.ox.ac.uk/cgi-bin/etcsl.cgi?text=t.4.24.1#|title=An adab to Ninlil (Ninlil A)|publisher=Electronic Text Corpus of Sumerian Literature|accessdate=2010-02-20}}</ref> [[Ninurta]] was the son of Enlil and Ninlil. He was worshipped as the god of war, agriculture, and one of the Sumerian wind gods. He was the patron deity of [[Girsu]] and one of the patron deities of [[Lagash]].\n\n[[Enki]] was god of freshwater, male fertility, and knowledge.<ref name=Black1992/>{{rp|75}} His most important cult center was the E-abzu temple in the city of [[Eridu]].<ref name=Black1992/>{{rp|75}} He was the patron and creator of humanity<ref name=Black1992/>{{rp|75}} and the sponsor of human culture.<ref name=Black1992/>{{rp|75}} His primary consort was [[Ninhursag]], the Sumerian goddess of the earth.<ref name=Black1992/>{{rp|140}} Ninhursag was worshipped in the cities of [[Kesh (Sumer)|Kesh]] and [[Adab (city)|Adab]].<ref name=Black1992/>{{rp|140}}\n\n[[File:Seal of Inanna, 2350-2150 BCE.jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|Ancient [[Akkadian Empire|Akkadian]] [[cylinder seal]] depicting Inanna resting her foot on the back of a lion while [[Ninshubur]] stands in front of her paying obeisance, c. 2334-2154 BC.<ref name=Wolkstein>{{citation|last1=Wolkstein|first1=Diane|last2=Kramer|first2=Samuel Noah|title=Inanna: Queen of Heaven and Earth: Her Stories and Hymns from Sumer|year=1983|publisher=Harper&Row Publishers|location=New York City, New York|isbn=0-06-090854-8|ref=harv}}</ref>{{rp|92, 193}}]]\n\nInanna was the Sumerian goddess of love, sexuality, prostitution, and war.<ref name=Black1992/>{{rp|109}} She was the divine personification of the planet [[Venus]], the morning and evening star.<ref name=Black1992/>{{rp|108\u2013109}} Her main cult center was the [[Eanna]] temple in [[Uruk]], which had been originally dedicated to An.<ref>{{cite book|last=Harris|first=Rivkah|title=Inanna-Ishtar as Paradox and a Coincidence of Opposites|journal=History of Religions|volume=30|issue=3|pages=261\u2013278|date=February 1991|jstor=1062957|doi=10.1086/463228|ref=harv}}</ref> Deified kings may have re-enacted the marriage of Inanna and [[Dumuzid the Shepherd|Dumuzid]] with priestesses.<ref name=Black1992/>{{rp|151, 157\u2013158}} Accounts of her parentage vary;<ref name=Black1992/>{{rp|108}} in most myths, she is usually presented as the daughter of Nanna and Ningal,<ref name=Wolkstein/>{{rp|ix-xi, xvi}} but, in other stories, she is the daughter of Enki or An along with an unknown mother.<ref name=Black1992/>{{rp|108}} The Sumerians had more myths about her than any other deity.<ref name=Wolkstein/>{{rp|xiii, xv}}<ref name=Kramer1961>{{citation|last1=Kramer|first1=Samuel Noah|title=Sumerian Mythology: A Study of Spiritual and Literary Achievement in the Third Millennium B.C.: Revised Edition|date=1961|publisher=University of Pennsylvania Press|location=Philadelphia, Pennsylvania|isbn=0-8122-1047-6|url=http://www.sacred-texts.com/ane/sum/}}</ref>{{rp|101}} Many of the myths involving her revolve around her attempts to usurp control of the other deities' domains.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Vanstiphout|first=H. L.|year=1984|title=Inanna/Ishtar as a Figure of Controversy.|journal=Struggles of Gods: Papers of the Groningen Work Group for the Study of the History of Religions|volume=31|publisher=Mouton Publishers|location=Berlin|url=https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=mQnv_Wh3gCwC&oi=fnd&pg=PA225&dq=origins+of+Inanna&ots=8Q5lsRgVqA&sig=-KngoT7xSjI9TTNf3k-rI43FGP4#v=onepage&q=origins%20of%20Inanna&f=false|pages=225\u2013228|isbn=90-279-3460-6}}</ref>\n\n[[Utu]] was god of the sun, whose primary center of worship was the E-babbar temple in [[Sippar]].<ref name=Utu>{{cite web|url=http://etcsl.orinst.ox.ac.uk/cgi-bin/etcsl.cgi?text=t.4.32.2#|title=A hymn to Utu (Utu B)|publisher=Electronic Text Corpus of Sumerian Literature|accessdate=2010-02-20}}</ref> Utu was principally regarded as a dispenser of justice;<ref name=Nemet1998/>{{rp|184}} he was believed to protect the righteous and punish the wicked.<ref name=Nemet1998/>{{rp|184}} [[Sin (mythology)|Nanna]] was god of the moon and of wisdom. He was the father of Utu and one of the patron deities of [[Ur]].<ref name=Nanna>{{cite web|url=http://etcsl.orinst.ox.ac.uk/cgi-bin/etcsl.cgi?text=t.4.13.01#|title=A balbale to Suen (Nanna A)|publisher=Electronic Text Corpus of Sumerian Literature|accessdate=2010-02-20}}</ref> He may have also been the father of Inanna and Ereshkigal. [[Ningal]] was the wife of Nanna,<ref name=Ningal>{{cite web|url=http://etcsl.orinst.ox.ac.uk/cgi-bin/etcsl.cgi?text=t.4.13.02#|title=A balbale to Nanna (Nanna B)|publisher=Electronic Text Corpus of Sumerian Literature|accessdate=2010-02-20}}</ref> as well as the mother of Utu, Inanna, and Ereshkigal.\n\n[[Ereshkigal]] was the goddess of the Sumerian [[Underworld]], which was known as [[Kur]].<ref name=Nemet1998/>{{rp|184}} She was Inanna's older sister.<ref>{{cite web|title=Inana's descent to the nether world|url=http://etcsl.orinst.ox.ac.uk/cgi-bin/etcsl.cgi?text=t.1.4.1&display=Crit&charenc=gcirc&lineid=t141.p30#t141.p30|website=The Electronic Text Corpus of Sumerian Literature|publisher=Oxford University|accessdate=17 June 2017}}</ref> In later myth, her husband was the god [[Nergal]].<ref name=Nemet1998/>{{rp|184}} The gatekeeper of the underworld was the god [[Neti (deity)|Neti]].<ref name=Nemet1998/>{{rp|184}}\n\n[[Nammu]] was the primeval sea (Engur), who gave birth to An (heaven) and Ki (earth) and the first deities; she eventually became known as the goddess [[Tiamat]]. [[Anu|An]] was the ancient Sumerian god of the heavens. He was the ancestor of all the other major deities<ref>{{cite web|last1=Brisch|first1=Nicole|title=Anunna (Anunnaku, Anunnaki) (a group of gods)|url=http://oracc.museum.upenn.edu/amgg/listofdeities/anunna/|website=Ancient Mesopotamian Gods and Goddesses|publisher=University of Pennsylvania Museum|accessdate=17 June 2017}}</ref> and the original patron deity of [[Uruk]].\n\n==Legacy==\n===Akkadians===\n[[File:Chaos Monster and Sun God.png|thumb|upright=1.3|[[Assyria]]n stone relief from the temple of Ninurta at [[Kalhu]], showing the god with his thunderbolts pursuing [[Anz\u00fb]], who has stolen the [[Tablet of Destinies (mythic item)|Tablet of Destinies]] from Enlil's sanctuary<ref name=Black1992/>{{rp|142}} ([[Austen Henry Layard]] ''Monuments of Nineveh'', 2nd Series, 1853)]]\n\nThe Sumerians had an ongoing linguistic and cultural exchange with the Semitic [[Akkadian language|Akkadian]] peoples in northern Mesopotamia for generations prior to the usurpation of their territories by [[Sargon of Akkad]] in 2340 BC. Sumerian mythology and religious practices were rapidly integrated into Akkadian culture,<ref name=TheSumerians>{{cite web|url= http://wsu.edu/~dee/MESO/SUMER.HTM|title= Mesopotamia: the Sumerians|publisher= Washington State University|access-date= 2009-06-22|url-status= dead|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20090718065010/http://www.wsu.edu/~dee/MESO/SUMER.HTM|archive-date= 2009-07-18|df= }}</ref> presumably blending with the original Akkadian belief systems that have been mostly lost to history. Sumerian deities developed Akkadian counterparts. Some remained virtually the same until later Babylonian and Assyrian rule. The Sumerian god An, for example, developed the Akkadian counterpart Anu; the Sumerian god Enki became [[Ea (Babylonian god)|Ea]]. The gods Ninurta and Enlil kept their original Sumerian names.{{Citation needed|date=May 2009}}\n\n===Babylonians===\n{{further|Babylonian religion}}\nThe [[Amorite]] Babylonians gained dominance over southern [[Mesopotamia]] by the mid-17th century BC. During the [[Babylonians#Old Babylonian period|Old Babylonian Period]], the Sumerian and Akkadian languages were retained for religious purposes; the majority of Sumerian mythological literature known to historians today comes from the Old Babylonian Period,<ref name=\"ETCSL\"/> either in the form of transcribed Sumerian texts (most notably the Babylonian version of the ''[[Epic of Gilgamesh]]'') or in the form of Sumerian and Akkadian influences within Babylonian mythological literature (most notably the ''[[En\u00fbma Eli\u0161]]''). The Sumerian-Akkadian pantheon was altered, most notably with the introduction of a new supreme deity, [[Marduk]]. The Sumerian goddess Inanna also developed the counterpart [[Ishtar]] during the Old Babylonian Period.\n\n===Hurrians===\n{{Main|Hurrians}}\nThe Hurrians adopted the Akkadian god Anu into their pantheon sometime no later than 1200 BC. Other Sumerian and Akkadian deities adapted into the Hurrian pantheon include Ayas, the Hurrian counterpart to Ea; Shaushka, the Hurrian counterpart to Ishtar; and the goddess [[Ninlil]],<ref name=Hurrians>{{cite web| url= http://home.comcast.net/~chris.s/hittite-ref.html#a2 |title= Hurrian Mythology REF 1.2|publisher=Christopher B. Siren|accessdate=2009-06-23}}</ref> whose mythos had been drastically expanded by the Babylonians.{{Citation needed|date=May 2009}}\n\n===Parallels===\nSome stories recorded in the older parts of the Hebrew Bible  bear strong similarities to the stories in Sumerian mythology. For example, the biblical account of [[Noah]] and the Great Flood bears a striking resemblance to the [[Deluge myth#Sumerian|Sumerian deluge myth]], recorded in a Sumerian tablet discovered at [[Nippur]].<ref name=Kramer1972>{{cite book|last1=Kramer|first1=Samuel Noah|title=Sumerian Mythology: A Study of Spiritual and Literary Achievement in the Third Millennium B.C.|date=1972|publisher=University of Pennsylvania Press|location=Philadelphia|isbn=0812210476|edition=Rev.}}</ref>{{rp|97\u2013101}} The Judaic underworld [[Sheol]] is very similar in description with the Sumerian [[Kur]], ruled by the goddess [[Ereshkigal]], as well as the Babylonian underworld [[Irkalla]]. Sumerian scholar [[Samuel Noah Kramer]] has also noted similarities between many Sumerian and Akkadian \"proverbs\" and the later Hebrew proverbs, many of which are featured in the [[Book of Proverbs]].<ref name=Kramer1956>{{cite book|last1=Kramer|first1=Samuel Noah|title=From the Tablets of Sumer.|date=1956|publisher=The Falcon's Wing Press|asin=B000S97EZ2}}</ref>{{rp|133\u2013135}}\n\n==Genealogy of the Sumerian deities==\n{{Sumerian Gods Genealogy}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Asia}}\n*[[Religions of the ancient Near East]]\n*[[Ancient Semitic religion]]\n*[[Babylonian religion]]\n*[[Me (mythology)|Mes]]\n*[[Mesopotamian mythology]]\n*[[Sumerian literature]]\n*[[Zuism]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://oracc.museum.upenn.edu/amgg/ Ancient Mesopotamian Gods and Goddesses], on Oracc\n{{Gutenberg|no=48094|name=Sumerian Hymns from Cuneiform Texts in the British Museum}} (Transcription of  book from 1908)\n\n{{Sumerian mythology}}\n{{Religion topics |ancient}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sumerian Religion}}\n[[Category:Mesopotamian mythology]]\n[[Category:3rd millennium BC in religion]]\n[[Category:Archaeology of Iraq]]\n[[Category:Polytheism]]\n[[Category:Sumer]]\n", "text_old": "{{multiple image|perrow=2|total_width=270|caption_align=center\n| align    = right\n| direction =vertical\n| header=Sumerian religion\n| image1   = Wall plaque from Ur 2500 BCE.jpg\n| caption1 = Wall plaque showing libations by devotees and a naked priest, to a seated god and a temple. [[Ur]], 2500 BCE.<ref>For a better image: [https://cdli.ucla.edu/dl/photo/P480697_d.jpg]</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Art of the First Cities: The Third Millennium B.C. from the Mediterranean to the Indus |date=2003 |publisher=Metropolitan Museum of Art |isbn=978-1-58839-043-1 |page=[https://archive.org/details/artoffirstcities0000unse/page/n152 74] |url=https://archive.org/details/artoffirstcities0000unse |url-access=registration |language=en}}</ref>\n| footer=\n}}\n{{Meso myth}}\n{{Ancient Near East mythology}}\n'''Sumerian religion''' was the [[religion]] practiced and adhered to by the people of [[Sumer]], the first [[literacy|literate]] civilization of [[ancient Mesopotamia]]. The Sumerians regarded their [[deity|divinities]] as responsible for all matters pertaining to the natural and social orders.<ref name=Kramer1963>{{cite book|last1=Kramer|first1=Samuel Noah|title=The Sumerians: Their History, Culture, and Character|date=1963|publisher=The Univ. of Chicago Press|location=|isbn=0-226-45238-7|url=https://archive.org/details/sumerianstheirhi00samu|url-access=registration}}</ref>{{rp|3\u20134}}\n \nBefore the beginning of kingship in Sumer, the city-states were effectively ruled by theocratic priests and religious officials. Later, this role was supplanted by kings, but priests continued to exert great influence on Sumerian society. In early times, Sumerian temples were simple, one-room structures, sometimes built on elevated platforms. Towards the end of Sumerian civilization, these temples developed into [[ziggurat]]s\u2014tall, pyramidal structures with sanctuaries at the tops.\n\nThe Sumerians believed that the universe had come into being through a series of [[Creation myth|cosmic births]]. First, [[Nammu]], the primeval waters, gave birth to [[Anu|An]] (the sky) and [[Ki (goddess)|Ki]] (the earth), who mated together and produced a son named [[Enlil]]. Enlil separated heaven from earth and claimed the earth as his domain. Humans were believed to have been created by [[Enki]], the son of An and Nammu. [[Heaven]] was reserved exclusively for deities and, upon their deaths, all mortals' spirits, regardless of their behavior while alive, were believed to go to [[Kur]], a cold, dark cavern deep beneath the earth, which was ruled by the goddess [[Ereshkigal]]  and where the only food available was dry dust. In later times, Ereshkigal was believed to rule alongside her husband [[Nergal]], the god of death.\n\nThe major deities in the Sumerian pantheon included An, the god of the heavens, Enlil, the god of wind and storm, [[Enki]], the god of water and human culture, [[Ninhursag]], the goddess of fertility and the earth, [[Utu]], the god of the sun and justice, and his father [[Sin (mythology)|Nanna]], the god of the moon. During the [[Akkadian Empire|Akkadian Period]] and afterward, [[Inanna]], the goddess of sex, beauty, and warfare, was widely venerated across Sumer and appeared in many myths, including the famous story of her [[Inanna#Descent into the Underworld|descent into the Underworld]].\n\nSumerian religion heavily influenced [[Mesopotamian mythology|the religious beliefs of later Mesopotamian peoples]]; elements of it are retained in the mythologies and religions of the [[Hurrians]], [[Akkadian Empire|Akkadians]], [[Babylonians]], [[Assyria]]ns, and other Middle Eastern culture groups. Scholars of comparative mythology have noticed many parallels between the stories of the ancient Sumerians and those recorded later in the early parts of the [[Hebrew Bible]].\n\n==Worship==\n\n===Written cuneiform===\n[[File:Temple evolution in cuneiform (sound E).jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|Evolution of the word \"Temple\" ([[Sumerian language|Sumerian]]: \"[[\u00c9 (temple)|\u00c9]]\") in [[cuneiform]], from a 2500 BCE relief in [[Ur]], to Assyrian cuneiform circa 600 BCE.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Budge |first1=E. A. Wallis (Ernst Alfred Wallis) |title=A guide to the Babylonian and Assyrian antiquities |date=1922 |publisher=British Museum |page=[https://archive.org/details/guidetobabylonia00briiala/page/22 22] |url=https://archive.org/details/guidetobabylonia00briiala}}</ref>]]\nSumerian myths were passed down through the [[oral tradition]] until the invention of writing (the earliest myth discovered so far, the [[Epic of Gilgamesh]], is Sumerian and is written on a series of fractured clay tablets). Early Sumerian [[cuneiform]] was used primarily as a record-keeping tool; it was not until the late [[History of Sumer#Early Dynastic period|early dynastic period]] that religious writings first became prevalent as temple praise hymns<ref name=ETCSL>{{cite web|url=http://etcsl.orinst.ox.ac.uk/edition2/literature.php|title=Sumerian Literature|publisher=Electronic Text Corpus of Sumerian Literature|accessdate=2009-06-22}}</ref> and as a form of \"incantation\" called the ''nam-\u0161ub'' (prefix + \"to cast\").<ref name=Lexicon>{{cite web| url=http://www.sumerian.org/sumerian.pdf |title=The Sumerian Lexicon|publisher=John A. Halloran|accessdate=2009-06-23}}</ref> These tablets were also made of stone clay or stone, and they used a small pick to make the symbols.\n\n===Architecture===\n{{Main|Sumerian architecture}}\n[[File:Plaque_with_libation_scene_BM_120850.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Plaque with a libation scene. 2550-2250 BCE, [[Royal Cemetery at Ur]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Art of the First Cities: The Third Millennium B.C. from the Mediterranean to the Indus |date=2003 |publisher=Metropolitan Museum of Art |isbn=978-1-58839-043-1 |page=[https://archive.org/details/artoffirstcities0000unse/page/n153 75] |url=https://archive.org/details/artoffirstcities0000unse |url-access=registration |language=en}}</ref><ref>Found loose in soil at the cemetery {{cite book |last1=Hall |first1=H. R. (Harry Reginald) |last2=Woolley |first2=Leonard |last3=Legrain |first3=Leon |title=Ur excavations |date=1900 |publisher=Trustees of the Two Museums by the aid of a grant from the Carnegie Corporation of New York |page=525 |url=https://archive.org/details/urexcavations186385join/page/524/mode/2up/search/U.+7900}}</ref>]]\nIn the Sumerian city-states, temple complexes originally were small, elevated one-room structures. In the early dynastic period, temples developed raised terraces and multiple rooms. Toward the end of the Sumerian civilization, [[ziggurats]] became the preferred temple structure for Mesopotamian religious centers.<ref name=BYU>{{cite web| url=http://mi.byu.edu/publications/books/?bookid=21&chapid=112 |title=Inside a Sumerian Temple|publisher=The Neal A. Maxwell Institute for Religious Scholarship at Brigham Young University |accessdate=2009-06-22}}</ref>\nTemples served as cultural, religious, and political headquarters until approximately 2500 BC, with the rise of military kings known as [[Lugal|Lu-gal]]s (\u201cman\u201d + \u201cbig\u201d)<ref name=\"Lexicon\"/> after which time the political and military leadership was often housed in separate \"palace\" complexes.\n\n===Priesthood===\n[[File:Sumerian Worshiper.JPG|thumb|Statuette of a Sumerian worshipper from the [[Early Dynastic Period (Mesopotamia)|Early Dynastic Period]], ca. 2800-2300 BC]]\n\nUntil the advent of the lugals, Sumerian city states were under a virtually [[Theocracy|theocratic]] government controlled by various [[EN (cuneiform)|En]] or [[Ens\u00ed]], who served as the [[high priest]]s of the cults of the city gods. (Their female equivalents were known as [[NIN (cuneiform)|Nin]].) Priests were responsible for continuing the cultural and religious traditions of their city-state, and were viewed as mediators between humans and the cosmic and terrestrial forces. The priesthood resided full-time in temple complexes, and administered matters of state including the large [[irrigation| irrigation processes]] necessary for the civilization's survival.\n\n===Ceremony===\nDuring the [[Third Dynasty of Ur]], the Sumerian city-state of [[Lagash]] was said to have had sixty-two \"lamentation priests\" who were accompanied by 180 vocalists and instrumentalists.\n\n==Cosmology==\nThe Sumerians envisioned the universe as a closed dome surrounded by a primordial saltwater sea.<ref name=Firmament>{{cite web| url=http://faculty.gordon.edu/hu/bi/Ted_Hildebrandt/OTeSources/01-Genesis/Text/Articles-Books/Seely-Firmament-WTJ.pdf |title=The Firmament and the Water Above|publisher=Westminster Theological Journal 53 (1991), 232-233|accessdate=2010-02-20}}</ref> Underneath the terrestrial earth, which formed the base of the dome, existed an underworld and a freshwater ocean called the [[Aps\u00fb]]. The deity of the dome-shaped [[firmament]] was named [[An (god)|An]]; that of the earth was named [[Ki (goddess)|Ki]]. First the underground world was believed to be an extension of the goddess Ki, but later developed into the concept of [[Kur]]. The primordial saltwater sea was named [[Nammu]], who became known as [[Tiamat]] during and after the [[Third Dynasty of Ur|Sumerian Renaissance]].\n\n===Creation story===\n{{Main|Sumerian creation myth}}\n{{multiple image|perrow=2|total_width=450|caption_align=center\n| align    = right\n| direction =horizontal\n| header=Early religious relief (c.2700 BCE)\n| image1   = Carved figure feathers Louvre AO221.jpg\n| caption1 = \n| image2   = Tablet of the figure with feathers, circa 2700 BCE, Girsu, Sumer.jpg\n| footer=Carved figure with feathers. The king-priest, wearing a net skirt and a hat with leaves or feathers, stands before the door of a temple, symbolized by two great maces. The inscription mentions the god [[Ningirsu]]. [[Early Dynastic Period (Mesopotamia)|Early Dynastic Period]], circa 2700 BCE.<ref>{{cite web |title=Louvre Museum Official Website |url=http://cartelen.louvre.fr/cartelen/visite?srv=car_not_frame&idNotice=11372 |website=cartelen.louvre.fr}}</ref>\n}}\nThe main source of information about the Sumerian creation myth is the prologue to the epic poem ''[[Gilgamesh, Enkidu, and the Netherworld]]'',<ref name=Kramer1961/>{{rp|30\u201333}} which briefly describes the process of creation: originally, there was only [[Nammu]], the primeval sea.<ref name=Kramer1961/>{{rp|37\u201340}} Then, Nammu gave birth to [[Anu|An]], the sky, and [[Ki (goddess)|Ki]], the earth.<ref name=Kramer1961/>{{rp|37\u201340}} An and Ki mated with each other, causing Ki to give birth to [[Enlil]], the god of wind, rain, and storm.<ref name=Kramer1961/>{{rp|37\u201340}} Enlil separated An from Ki and carried off the earth as his domain, while An carried off the sky.<ref name=Kramer1961/>{{rp|37\u201341}}\n\n===Heaven===\n{{Main|Seven Heavens}}\nThe ancient Mesopotamians regarded the sky as a series of domes (usually three, but sometimes seven) covering the [[flat earth]].<ref name=Nemet1998>{{citation|last=Nemet-Nejat|first=Karen Rhea|authorlink=Karen Rhea Nemet-Nejat|date=1998|title=Daily Life in Ancient Mesopotamia|publisher=Greenwood|series=Daily Life|isbn=978-0313294976|url=https://archive.org/details/dailylifeinancie00neme}}</ref>{{rp|180}} Each dome was made of a different kind of precious stone.<ref name=Nemet1998/>{{rp|203}} The lowest dome of heaven was made of [[jasper]] and was the home of the [[star]]s.<ref name=Lambert2016>{{cite book|last1=Lambert|first1=W. G.|title=Ancient Mesopotamian Religion and Mythology: Selected Essays|date=2016|publisher=Mohr Siebeck|location=Tuebingen, Germany|editor1-last=George|editor1-first=A. R.|editor2-last=Oshima|editor2-first=T. M.|isbn=978-3-16-153674-8|series=Orientalische Religionen in der Antike|volume=15|page=118|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dTLWQddp8zwC&pg=PA118&dq=Heaven+in+Mesopotamian+religion&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjFwqeqx_DWAhVLzoMKHVuFArIQ6AEIKjAB#v=onepage&q=Heaven%20in%20Mesopotamian%20religion&f=false}}</ref> The middle dome of heaven was made of ''saggilmut'' stone and was the abode of the [[Igigi]].<ref name=Lambert2016/> The highest and outermost dome of heaven was made of ''lulud\u0101n\u012btu'' stone and was personified as [[Anu|An]], the god of the sky.<ref>{{citation|last=Stephens|first=Kathryn|title=An/Anu (god): Mesopotamian sky-god, one of the supreme deities; known as An in Sumerian and Anu in Akkadian|url=http://oracc.museum.upenn.edu/amgg/listofdeities/an/|website=Ancient Mesopotamian Gods and Goddesses|publisher=University of Pennsylvania Museum|date=2013}}</ref><ref name=Lambert2016/> The [[Astronomical object|celestial bodies]] were equated with specific deities as well.<ref name=Nemet1998/>{{rp|203}} The planet [[Venus]] was believed to be [[Inanna]], the goddess of love, sex, and war.<ref name=Black1992>{{citation|last=Black |first=Jeremy |first2=Anthony |last2=Green |title=Gods, Demons and Symbols of Ancient Mesopotamia: An Illustrated Dictionary |publisher=The British Museum Press|year=1992 |isbn= 0-7141-1705-6}}</ref>{{rp|108\u2013109}}<ref name=Nemet1998/>{{rp|203}} The [[sun]] was her brother [[Utu]], the god of justice,<ref name=Nemet1998/>{{rp|203}} and the [[moon]] was their father [[Sin (mythology)|Nanna]].<ref name=Nemet1998/>{{rp|203}} Ordinary mortals could not go to heaven because it was the abode of the gods alone.<ref name=\"Wright2000\">{{cite book|last1=Wright|first1=J. Edward|title=The Early History of Heaven|date=2000|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Oxford, England|isbn=0-19-513009-X|page=29|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lKvMeMorNBEC&pg=PA26&dq=Heaven+in+Mesopotamian+religion&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjFwqeqx_DWAhVLzoMKHVuFArIQ6AEIOzAE#v=onepage&q=Heaven%20in%20Mesopotamian%20religion&f=false}}</ref> Instead, after a person died, his or her soul went to [[Kur]] (later known as [[Irkalla]]), a dark shadowy [[underworld]], located deep below the surface of the earth.<ref name=\"Wright2000\"/><ref name=Choksi2014>{{citation|last=Choksi|first=M.|date=2014|title=Ancient Mesopotamian Beliefs in the Afterlife|url=http://www.ancient.eu/article/701/|website=Ancient History Encyclopedia|publisher=ancient.eu}}</ref>\n\n===Afterlife===\n{{main|Kur}}\n[[File:Dumuzi aux enfers.jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|Ancient Sumerian [[cylinder seal]] impression showing the god [[Dumuzid the Shepherd|Dumuzid]] being tortured in the [[Kur|Underworld]] by ''[[gallu|galla]]'' demons]]\n[[File:VAM - Rollsiegel 1.jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|Devotional scene, with Temple.]]\nThe [[Sumer]]ian afterlife was a dark, dreary cavern located deep below the ground,<ref name=Choksi2014/><ref>{{cite journal|last=Barret|first=C. E.|date=2007|title=Was dust their food and clay their bread?: Grave goods, the Mesopotamian afterlife, and the liminal role of Inana/I\u0161tar|journal=Journal of Ancient Near Eastern Religions|volume=7|issue=1|pages=7\u201365|location=Leiden, The Netherlands|publisher=Brill|url=http://booksandjournals.brillonline.com/content/journals/10.1163/156921207781375123|doi=10.1163/156921207781375123|issn=1569-2116}}</ref> where inhabitants were believed to continue \"a shadowy version of life on earth\".<ref name=Choksi2014/> This bleak domain was known as [[Kur]],<ref name=Black1992/>{{rp|114}} and was believed to be ruled by the goddess [[Ereshkigal]].<ref name=Choksi2014/><ref name=Nemet1998/>{{rp|184}} All souls went to the same afterlife,<ref name=Choksi2014/> and a person's actions during life had no effect on how the person would be treated in the world to come.<ref name=Choksi2014/>\n\nThe souls in Kur were believed to eat nothing but dry [[dust]]<ref name=Black1992/>{{rp|58}} and family members of the deceased would ritually pour [[libation]]s into the dead person's grave through a clay pipe, thereby allowing the dead to drink.<ref name=Black1992/>{{rp|58}} Nonetheless, funerary evidence indicates that some people believed that the goddess [[Inanna]], Ereshkigal's younger sister, had the power to award her devotees with special favors in the afterlife.<ref name=Choksi2014/> During the [[Third Dynasty of Ur]], it was believed that a person's treatment in the afterlife depended on how he or she was buried;<ref name=Black1992/>{{rp|58}} those that had been given sumptuous burials would be treated well,<ref name=Black1992/>{{rp|58}} but those who had been given poor burials would fare poorly.<ref name=Black1992/>{{rp|58}}\n\nThe entrance to Kur was believed to be located in the [[Zagros mountains]] in the far east.<ref name=Black1992/>{{rp|114}} It had seven gates, through which a soul needed to pass.<ref name=Choksi2014/> The god [[Neti (deity)|Neti]] was the gatekeeper.<ref name=Nemet1998/>{{rp|184}}<ref name=Black1992/>{{rp|86}} Ereshkigal's ''sukkal'', or messenger, was the god [[Namtar]].<ref name=Black1992/>{{rp|134}}<ref name=Nemet1998/>{{rp|184}} ''[[Gallu|Galla]]'' were a class of demons that were believed to reside in the underworld;<ref name=Black1992/>{{rp|85}} their primary purpose appears to have been to drag unfortunate mortals back to Kur.<ref name=Black1992/>{{rp|85}} They are frequently referenced in magical texts,<ref name=Black1992/>{{rp|85\u201386}} and some texts describe them as being seven in number.<ref name=Black1992/>{{rp|85\u201386}} Several extant poems describe the ''galla'' dragging the god [[Dumuzid the Shepherd|Dumuzid]] into the underworld.<ref name=Black1992/>{{rp|86}} The later Mesopotamians knew this underworld by its [[East Semitic]] name: [[Irkalla]]. During the [[Akkadian Empire|Akkadian Period]], Ereshkigal's role as the ruler of the underworld was assigned to [[Nergal]], the god of death.<ref name=Choksi2014/><ref name=Nemet1998/>{{rp|184}} The Akkadians attempted to harmonize this dual rulership of the underworld by making Nergal Ereshkigal's husband.<ref name=Choksi2014/>\n\n==Pantheon==\n{{see also|List of Mesopotamian deities}}\n\n===Development===\n[[File:Mu\u0161\u1e2bu\u0161\u0161u on a vase of Gudea, circa 2100 BCE.jpg|thumb|upright=0.5|The dragon [[Mu\u0161\u1e2bu\u0161\u0161u]] on a vase of [[Gudea]], circa 2100 BCE.]]\nIt is generally agreed that Sumerian [[civilization]] began at some point between c. 4500 and 4000 BC, but the earliest historical records only date to around 2900 BC.<ref>{{cite book| last=Bertman| first=Stephen| title=Handbook to life in ancient Mesopotamia| year=2003| publisher=Facts on File| isbn=978-0-8160-4346-0| url=https://archive.org/details/handbooktolifein00bert| url-access=registration|page=[https://archive.org/details/handbooktolifein00bert/page/143 143]}}</ref> The Sumerians originally practiced a [[polytheistic]] religion, with [[anthropomorphic]] [[deity|deities]] representing cosmic and terrestrial forces in their world.<ref name=Nemet1998/>{{rp|178\u2013179}} The earliest [[Sumerian literature]] of the third millennium BC identifies four primary deities: [[Anu|An]], [[Enlil]], [[Ninhursag]], and [[Enki]]. These early deities were believed to occasionally behave mischievously towards each other, but were generally viewed as being involved in co-operative creative ordering.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Sources of the Old Testament: A Guide to the Religious Thought of the Old Testament in Context|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EG4CYbEbOrwC&pg=PA29|accessdate=7 May 2013|date=18 May 2004|publisher=Continuum International Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-567-08463-7|pages=29\u2013}}</ref>\n\nDuring the middle of the third millennium BC, Sumerian society became more urbanized.<ref name=Nemet1998/>{{rp|178\u2013179}} As a result of this, Sumerian deities began to lose their original associations with nature and became the patrons of various cities.<ref name=Nemet1998/>{{rp|179}} Each Sumerian city-state had its own specific patron deity,<ref name=Nemet1998/>{{rp|179}} who was believed to protect the city and defend its interests.<ref name=Nemet1998/>{{rp|179}} Lists of large numbers of Sumerian deities have been found. Their order of importance and the relationships between the deities has been examined during the study of [[cuneiform]] tablets.<ref>{{cite book|title=God in Translation: Deities in Cross-cultural Discourse in the Biblical World|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yvWlC0kUlkYC&pg=PA42|accessdate=7 May 2013|year=2010|publisher=Wm. B. Eerdmans Publishing|isbn=978-0-8028-6433-8|pages=42\u2013}}</ref>\n\nDuring the late 2000s BC, the Sumerians were conquered by the [[Akkadian Empire|Akkadians]].<ref name=Nemet1998/>{{rp|179}} The Akkadians [[syncretism|syncretized]] their own gods with the Sumerian ones,<ref name=Nemet1998/>{{rp|179}} causing Sumerian religion to take on a Semitic coloration.<ref name=Nemet1998/>{{rp|179}} Male deities became dominant<ref name=Nemet1998/>{{rp|179}} and the gods completely lost their original associations with natural phenomena.<ref name=Nemet1998/>{{rp|179\u2013180}} People began to view the gods as living in a [[feudal society]] with [[class structure]].<ref name=Nemet1998/>{{rp|179\u2013181}} Powerful deities such as [[Enki]] and [[Inanna]] became seen as receiving their power from the chief god [[Enlil]].<ref name=Nemet1998/>{{rp|179\u2013180}}\n\n===Major deities===\n[[File:Ea (Babilonian) - EnKi (Sumerian).jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|Akkadian [[cylinder seal]] from sometime around 2300 BC or thereabouts depicting the deities [[Inanna]], [[Utu]], [[Enki]], and [[Isimud]]<ref name=Kramer1961/>{{rp|32\u201333}}]]\n\nThe majority of Sumerian deities belonged to a classification called the ''Anunna'' (\u201c[offspring] of [[An (mythology)|An]]\u201d), whereas seven deities, including Enlil and Inanna, belonged to a group of \u201cunderworld judges\" known as the ''[[Anunnaki]]'' (\u201c[offspring] of An\u201d + [[Ki (goddess)|Ki]]). During the [[Third Dynasty of Ur]], the Sumerian pantheon was said to include sixty times sixty (3600) deities.<ref name=Nemet1998/>{{rp|182}}\n\n[[Enlil]] was the god of air, wind, and storm.<ref name=Davidson2015>{{citation|last1=Coleman|first1=J. A.|last2=Davidson|first2=George|title=The Dictionary of Mythology: An A-Z of Themes, Legends, and Heroes|date=2015|publisher=Arcturus Publishing Limited|location=London, England|isbn=978-1-78404-478-7|page=108}}</ref>{{rp|108}} He was also the chief god of the Sumerian pantheon<ref name=Davidson2015 />{{rp|108}}<ref>{{citation|first=Samuel Noah|last=Kramer|title=The Sumerian Deluge Myth: Reviewed and Revised|journal=Anatolian Studies|volume=33|date=1983|jstor=3642699|publisher=British Institute at Ankara|doi=10.2307/3642699}}</ref>{{rp|115\u2013121}} and the patron deity of the city of [[Nippur]].<ref name=Schneider2011>{{citation|last=Schneider|first=Tammi J.|title=An Introduction to Ancient Mesopotamian Religion|publisher=William B. Eerdman's Publishing Company|location=Grand Rapids, Michigan|date=2011|isbn=978-0-8028-2959-7|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2HfU9gv0fXYC&pg=PA58}}</ref>{{rp|58}}<ref>{{citation|last=Hallo|first=William W.|article=Review: Enki and the Theology of Eridu|title=Journal of the American Oriental Society|volume=116|issue=2|date=1996}}</ref>{{rp|231\u2013234}} His primary consort was [[Ninlil]], the goddess of the south wind,<ref>{{citation|last1=Black|first1=Jeremy A.|last2=Cunningham|first2=Graham|last3=Robson|first3=Eleanor|title=The Literature of Ancient Sumer|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=a1W2mTtGVV4C&pg=PA106|date=2006|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-929633-0}}</ref>{{rp|106}} who was one of the matron deities of [[Nippur]] and was believed to reside in the same temple as Enlil.<ref name=Ninlil>{{cite web|url=http://etcsl.orinst.ox.ac.uk/cgi-bin/etcsl.cgi?text=t.4.24.1#|title=An adab to Ninlil (Ninlil A)|publisher=Electronic Text Corpus of Sumerian Literature|accessdate=2010-02-20}}</ref> [[Ninurta]] was the son of Enlil and Ninlil. He was worshipped as the god of war, agriculture, and one of the Sumerian wind gods. He was the patron deity of [[Girsu]] and one of the patron deities of [[Lagash]].\n\n[[Enki]] was god of freshwater, male fertility, and knowledge.<ref name=Black1992/>{{rp|75}} His most important cult center was the E-abzu temple in the city of [[Eridu]].<ref name=Black1992/>{{rp|75}} He was the patron and creator of humanity<ref name=Black1992/>{{rp|75}} and the sponsor of human culture.<ref name=Black1992/>{{rp|75}} His primary consort was [[Ninhursag]], the Sumerian goddess of the earth.<ref name=Black1992/>{{rp|140}} Ninhursag was worshipped in the cities of [[Kesh (Sumer)|Kesh]] and [[Adab (city)|Adab]].<ref name=Black1992/>{{rp|140}}\n\n[[File:Seal of Inanna, 2350-2150 BCE.jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|Ancient [[Akkadian Empire|Akkadian]] [[cylinder seal]] depicting Inanna resting her foot on the back of a lion while [[Ninshubur]] stands in front of her paying obeisance, c. 2334-2154 BC.<ref name=Wolkstein>{{citation|last1=Wolkstein|first1=Diane|last2=Kramer|first2=Samuel Noah|title=Inanna: Queen of Heaven and Earth: Her Stories and Hymns from Sumer|year=1983|publisher=Harper&Row Publishers|location=New York City, New York|isbn=0-06-090854-8|ref=harv}}</ref>{{rp|92, 193}}]]\n\nInanna was the Sumerian goddess of love, sexuality, prostitution, and war.<ref name=Black1992/>{{rp|109}} She was the divine personification of the planet [[Venus]], the morning and evening star.<ref name=Black1992/>{{rp|108\u2013109}} Her main cult center was the [[Eanna]] temple in [[Uruk]], which had been originally dedicated to An.<ref>{{cite book|last=Harris|first=Rivkah|title=Inanna-Ishtar as Paradox and a Coincidence of Opposites|journal=History of Religions|volume=30|issue=3|pages=261\u2013278|date=February 1991|jstor=1062957|doi=10.1086/463228|ref=harv}}</ref> Deified kings may have re-enacted the marriage of Inanna and [[Dumuzid the Shepherd|Dumuzid]] with priestesses.<ref name=Black1992/>{{rp|151, 157\u2013158}} Accounts of her parentage vary;<ref name=Black1992/>{{rp|108}} in most myths, she is usually presented as the daughter of Nanna and Ningal,<ref name=Wolkstein/>{{rp|ix-xi, xvi}} but, in other stories, she is the daughter of Enki or An along with an unknown mother.<ref name=Black1992/>{{rp|108}} The Sumerians had more myths about her than any other deity.<ref name=Wolkstein/>{{rp|xiii, xv}}<ref name=Kramer1961>{{citation|last1=Kramer|first1=Samuel Noah|title=Sumerian Mythology: A Study of Spiritual and Literary Achievement in the Third Millennium B.C.: Revised Edition|date=1961|publisher=University of Pennsylvania Press|location=Philadelphia, Pennsylvania|isbn=0-8122-1047-6|url=http://www.sacred-texts.com/ane/sum/}}</ref>{{rp|101}} Many of the myths involving her revolve around her attempts to usurp control of the other deities' domains.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Vanstiphout|first=H. L.|year=1984|title=Inanna/Ishtar as a Figure of Controversy.|journal=Struggles of Gods: Papers of the Groningen Work Group for the Study of the History of Religions|volume=31|publisher=Mouton Publishers|location=Berlin|url=https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=mQnv_Wh3gCwC&oi=fnd&pg=PA225&dq=origins+of+Inanna&ots=8Q5lsRgVqA&sig=-KngoT7xSjI9TTNf3k-rI43FGP4#v=onepage&q=origins%20of%20Inanna&f=false|pages=225\u2013228|isbn=90-279-3460-6}}</ref>\n\n[[Utu]] was god of the sun, whose primary center of worship was the E-babbar temple in [[Sippar]].<ref name=Utu>{{cite web|url=http://etcsl.orinst.ox.ac.uk/cgi-bin/etcsl.cgi?text=t.4.32.2#|title=A hymn to Utu (Utu B)|publisher=Electronic Text Corpus of Sumerian Literature|accessdate=2010-02-20}}</ref> Utu was principally regarded as a dispenser of justice;<ref name=Nemet1998/>{{rp|184}} he was believed to protect the righteous and punish the wicked.<ref name=Nemet1998/>{{rp|184}} [[Sin (mythology)|Nanna]] was god of the moon and of wisdom. He was the father of Utu and one of the patron deities of [[Ur]].<ref name=Nanna>{{cite web|url=http://etcsl.orinst.ox.ac.uk/cgi-bin/etcsl.cgi?text=t.4.13.01#|title=A balbale to Suen (Nanna A)|publisher=Electronic Text Corpus of Sumerian Literature|accessdate=2010-02-20}}</ref> He may have also been the father of Inanna and Ereshkigal. [[Ningal]] was the wife of Nanna,<ref name=Ningal>{{cite web|url=http://etcsl.orinst.ox.ac.uk/cgi-bin/etcsl.cgi?text=t.4.13.02#|title=A balbale to Nanna (Nanna B)|publisher=Electronic Text Corpus of Sumerian Literature|accessdate=2010-02-20}}</ref> as well as the mother of Utu, Inanna, and Ereshkigal.\n\n[[Ereshkigal]] was the goddess of the Sumerian [[Underworld]], which was known as [[Kur]].<ref name=Nemet1998/>{{rp|184}} She was Inanna's older sister.<ref>{{cite web|title=Inana's descent to the nether world|url=http://etcsl.orinst.ox.ac.uk/cgi-bin/etcsl.cgi?text=t.1.4.1&display=Crit&charenc=gcirc&lineid=t141.p30#t141.p30|website=The Electronic Text Corpus of Sumerian Literature|publisher=Oxford University|accessdate=17 June 2017}}</ref> In later myth, her husband was the god [[Nergal]].<ref name=Nemet1998/>{{rp|184}} The gatekeeper of the underworld was the god [[Neti (deity)|Neti]].<ref name=Nemet1998/>{{rp|184}}\n\n[[Nammu]] was the primeval sea (Engur), who gave birth to An (heaven) and Ki (earth) and the first deities; she eventually became known as the goddess [[Tiamat]]. [[Anu|An]] was the ancient Sumerian god of the heavens. He was the ancestor of all the other major deities<ref>{{cite web|last1=Brisch|first1=Nicole|title=Anunna (Anunnaku, Anunnaki) (a group of gods)|url=http://oracc.museum.upenn.edu/amgg/listofdeities/anunna/|website=Ancient Mesopotamian Gods and Goddesses|publisher=University of Pennsylvania Museum|accessdate=17 June 2017}}</ref> and the original patron deity of [[Uruk]].\n\n==Legacy==\n===Akkadians===\n[[File:Chaos Monster and Sun God.png|thumb|upright=1.3|[[Assyria]]n stone relief from the temple of Ninurta at [[Kalhu]], showing the god with his thunderbolts pursuing [[Anz\u00fb]], who has stolen the [[Tablet of Destinies (mythic item)|Tablet of Destinies]] from Enlil's sanctuary<ref name=Black1992/>{{rp|142}} ([[Austen Henry Layard]] ''Monuments of Nineveh'', 2nd Series, 1853)]]\n\nThe Sumerians had an ongoing linguistic and cultural exchange with the Semitic [[Akkadian language|Akkadian]] peoples in northern Mesopotamia for generations prior to the usurpation of their territories by [[Sargon of Akkad]] in 2340 BC. Sumerian mythology and religious practices were rapidly integrated into Akkadian culture,<ref name=TheSumerians>{{cite web|url= http://wsu.edu/~dee/MESO/SUMER.HTM|title= Mesopotamia: the Sumerians|publisher= Washington State University|access-date= 2009-06-22|url-status= dead|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20090718065010/http://www.wsu.edu/~dee/MESO/SUMER.HTM|archive-date= 2009-07-18|df= }}</ref> presumably blending with the original Akkadian belief systems that have been mostly lost to history. Sumerian deities developed Akkadian counterparts. Some remained virtually the same until later Babylonian and Assyrian rule. The Sumerian god An, for example, developed the Akkadian counterpart Anu; the Sumerian god Enki became [[Ea (Babylonian god)|Ea]]. The gods Ninurta and Enlil kept their original Sumerian names.{{Citation needed|date=May 2009}}\n\n===Babylonians===\n{{further|Babylonian religion}}\nThe [[Amorite]] Babylonians gained dominance over southern [[Mesopotamia]] by the mid-17th century BC. During the [[Babylonians#Old Babylonian period|Old Babylonian Period]], the Sumerian and Akkadian languages were retained for religious purposes; the majority of Sumerian mythological literature known to historians today comes from the Old Babylonian Period,<ref name=\"ETCSL\"/> either in the form of transcribed Sumerian texts (most notably the Babylonian version of the ''[[Epic of Gilgamesh]]'') or in the form of Sumerian and Akkadian influences within Babylonian mythological literature (most notably the ''[[En\u00fbma Eli\u0161]]''). The Sumerian-Akkadian pantheon was altered, most notably with the introduction of a new supreme deity, [[Marduk]]. The Sumerian goddess Inanna also developed the counterpart [[Ishtar]] during the Old Babylonian Period.\n\n===Hurrians===\n{{Main|Hurrians}}\nThe Hurrians adopted the Akkadian god Anu into their pantheon sometime no later than 1200 BC. Other Sumerian and Akkadian deities adapted into the Hurrian pantheon include Ayas, the Hurrian counterpart to Ea; Shaushka, the Hurrian counterpart to Ishtar; and the goddess [[Ninlil]],<ref name=Hurrians>{{cite web| url= http://home.comcast.net/~chris.s/hittite-ref.html#a2 |title= Hurrian Mythology REF 1.2|publisher=Christopher B. Siren|accessdate=2009-06-23}}</ref> whose mythos had been drastically expanded by the Babylonians.{{Citation needed|date=May 2009}}\n\n===Parallels===\nSome stories recorded in the older parts of the Hebrew Bible  bear strong similarities to the stories in Sumerian mythology. For example, the biblical account of [[Noah]] and the Great Flood bears a striking resemblance to the [[Deluge myth#Sumerian|Sumerian deluge myth]], recorded in a Sumerian tablet discovered at [[Nippur]].<ref name=Kramer1972>{{cite book|last1=Kramer|first1=Samuel Noah|title=Sumerian Mythology: A Study of Spiritual and Literary Achievement in the Third Millennium B.C.|date=1972|publisher=University of Pennsylvania Press|location=Philadelphia|isbn=0812210476|edition=Rev.}}</ref>{{rp|97\u2013101}} The Judaic underworld [[Sheol]] is very similar in description with the Sumerian [[Kur]], ruled by the goddess [[Ereshkigal]], as well as the Babylonian underworld [[Irkalla]]. Sumerian scholar [[Samuel Noah Kramer]] has also noted similarities between many Sumerian and Akkadian \"proverbs\" and the later Hebrew proverbs, many of which are featured in the [[Book of Proverbs]].<ref name=Kramer1956>{{cite book|last1=Kramer|first1=Samuel Noah|title=From the Tablets of Sumer.|date=1956|publisher=The Falcon's Wing Press|asin=B000S97EZ2}}</ref>{{rp|133\u2013135}}\n\n==Genealogy of the Sumerian deities==\n{{Sumerian Gods Genealogy}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Asia}}\n*[[Religions of the ancient Near East]]\n*[[Ancient Semitic religion]]\n*[[Babylonian religion]]\n*[[Me (mythology)|Mes]]\n*[[Mesopotamian mythology]]\n*[[Sumerian literature]]\n*[[Zuism]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://oracc.museum.upenn.edu/amgg/ Ancient Mesopotamian Gods and Goddesses], on Oracc\n{{Gutenberg|no=48094|name=Sumerian Hymns from Cuneiform Texts in the British Museum}} (Transcription of  book from 1908)\n\n{{Sumerian mythology}}\n{{Religion topics |ancient}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sumerian Religion}}\n[[Category:Mesopotamian mythology]]\n[[Category:3rd millennium BC in religion]]\n[[Category:Archaeology of Iraq]]\n[[Category:Polytheism]]\n[[Category:Sumer]]\n", "name_user": "2405:201:3204:672a:988e:5088:40db:cef5", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sumerian_religion"}
{"title_page": "Kamalakanta Bhattacharya (Assam)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name = Kamalakanta Bhattacharya\n| image = Kamalakanta Bhattacharya.jpg\n| image_size = 250px\n| alt = \n| caption = \n| pseudonym = \n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = 23 December 1853<!-- {{Birth date and age|df=yes|Year|Month|Day}} -->\n| birth_place = Gorehagi, [[Biswanath Chariali]], [[Sonitpur district|Sonitpur]], [[Assam]]\n| death_date = 18  December 1936 <!-- {{Death date and age|df=yes|Year|Month|Day|Year|Month|Day}} -->\n| death_place = [[Guwahati]], Assam\n| resting_place = \n| occupation = \n| language = [[Assamese language|Assamese]]\n| nationality = [[India]]n\n| ethnicity = \n| citizenship = \n| education = \n| alma_mater = \n| period = \n| genre = \n| subject = \n| movement = \n| notableworks = \n| spouse = \n| partner = \n| children = \n| relatives = \n| influences = \n| influenced = \n| awards = \n| signature = \n| signature_alt = \n| website = \n| portaldisp = \n}}\n'''Kamalakanta Bhattacharya''' ({{lang-as|\u0995\u09ae\u09b2\u09be\u0995\u09be\u09a8\u09cd\u09a4 \u09ad\u099f\u09cd\u099f\u09be\u099a\u09be\u09f0\u09cd\u09af\u09cd\u09af}}; 1853\u20131936) was a prominent essayist and poet belonged to the Oronodoi era of [[Assamese literature]]. He was born in 23 December 1853 in Gorehagi village, [[Biswanath Chariali]], [[Sonitpur district]],  Assam. He was popularly known as 'Agnikobi' (\u0985\u0997\u09cd\u09a8\u09bf\u0995\u09ac\u09bf).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sonitpur.gov.in/culture.htm |title=culture |publisher=Sonitpur.gov.in |date= |accessdate=2013-05-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130822073644/http://sonitpur.gov.in/culture.htm |archive-date=22 August 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Politically, he was strongly nationalistic. He opposed the introduction of Bengali as the official language of Assam in 1871. At the annual meeting of the [[Indian National Congress]] in 1886 in [[Calcutta]], he participated as a delegate for Assam. In 1929 he sat as Secretary General of the Organization Culture [[Asam Sahitya Sabha]] ago. He was also the president of the Asam Sahitya Sabha in 1929 held at [[Jorhat district]], Assam.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vedanti.com/News/assam_sahitya_sabha_is_the_forem.htm |title=Asam Sahitya Sabha is the foremost and the most popular organization of Assam |publisher=Vedanti.com |accessdate=2013-05-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130926194342/http://www.vedanti.com/News/assam_sahitya_sabha_is_the_forem.htm |archivedate=2013-09-26 }}</ref> He campaigned for the abolition of the box security regulations and promoted the education of women. He also participated in the swadeshi movement in 1905-06.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=GE2o4QQV7UgC&lpg=PA52&dq=Kamalakanta%20Bhattacharya%20(Assam)&pg=PA52#v=onepage&q=Kamalakanta%20Bhattacharya%20(Assam)&f=false |title=Brahmo Samaj and North-East India - Dipankar Banerjee - Google Books |publisher=Books.google.co.in |date= |accessdate=2013-05-15|isbn=9788179751763 |year=2006 }}</ref>\n\n==Literary works==\n* ''Manat mor para Katha'' (autobiography)\n* ''Chintanala'' (\"The Fire of Thoughts\", a collection of poems, 1870)<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=bMsGmbALl5sC&lpg=PA95&dq=Kamalakanta%20Bhattacharya%20(Assam)&pg=PA78#v=onepage&q=Kamalakanta%20Bhattacharya%20(Assam)&f=false |title=Assamese Literature - S. N. Sharma - Google Books |publisher=Books.google.co.in |date= |accessdate=2013-05-15|isbn=9783447017367 |year=1976 }}</ref>\n* ''Chinta Tarangini'' (\"The Stream of Thought Waves\", a collection of poems, 1933)<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=sqBjpV9OzcsC&lpg=PA196&dq=Kamalakanta%20Bhattacharya%20(Assam)&pg=PA660#v=onepage&q=Kamalakanta%20Bhattacharya%20(Assam)&f=false |title=A History of Indian Literature 1911-1956: Struggle for Freedom: Triumph and ... - Sisir Kumar Das - Google Books |publisher=Books.google.co.in |date= |accessdate=2013-05-15|isbn=9788172017989 |year=1991 }}</ref>\n* ''Ashtabakrar Atmajivani''\n* ''Ashtabakra'' (poetry)\n\n==See also==\n* [[Assamese literature]]\n* [[History of Assamese literature]]\n* [[List of Asam Sahitya Sabha presidents]]\n* [[List of Assamese writers with their pen names]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://creative.sulekha.com/eminent-personalities-of-assam_467977_blog Short biography] at creative.sulekha.com.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070717115154/http://www.sarai.net/fellowships/independent/archival-submissions/fellowships-04-05/uddipan-dutta-the-growth-of-print-nationalism-and-assamese-identity-in-two-early-assamese-magazines/page-8/ Few lines by Kamalakanta Bhattacharya from his article \"Jatiyo Unnoti\"] at sarai.net.\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bhattacharya, Kamalakanta}}\n[[Category:Writers from Assam]]\n[[Category:Asom Sahitya Sabha Presidents]]\n[[Category:1853 births]]\n[[Category:1936 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Sonitpur district]]\n[[Category:Assamese-language poets]]\n[[Category:19th-century Indian poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian poets]]\n[[Category:Indian male essayists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian essayists]]\n[[Category:19th-century Indian essayists]]\n[[Category:19th-century male writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name = Kamalakanta Bhattacharya\n| image = Kamalakanta Bhattacharya.jpg\n| image_size = 250px\n| alt = \n| caption = \n| pseudonym = \n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = 23 December 1853<!-- {{Birth date and age|df=yes|Year|Month|Day}} -->\n| birth_place = Gorehagi, [[Biswanath Chariali]], [[Sonitpur district|Sonitpur]], [[Assam]]\n| death_date = 18  December 1936 <!-- {{Death date and age|df=yes|Year|Month|Day|Year|Month|Day}} -->\n| death_place = [[Guwahati]], Assam\n| resting_place = \n| occupation = \n| language = [[Assamese language|Assamese]]\n| nationality = [[India]]n\n| ethnicity = \n| citizenship = \n| education = \n| alma_mater = \n| period = \n| genre = \n| subject = \n| movement = \n| notableworks = \n| spouse = \n| partner = \n| children = \n| relatives = \n| influences = \n| influenced = \n| awards = \n| signature = \n| signature_alt = \n| website = \n| portaldisp = \n}}\n'''Kamalakanta Bhattacharya''' ({{lang-as|\u0995\u09ae\u09b2\u09be\u0995\u09be\u09a8\u09cd\u09a4 \u09ad\u099f\u09cd\u099f\u09be\u099a\u09be\u09f0\u09cd\u09af\u09cd\u09af}}; 1853\u20131936) was a prominent essayist and poet belonged to the Oronodoi era of [[Assamese literature]]. He was born in 23 December 1853 in Gorehagi village, [[Biswanath Chariali]], [[Sonitpur district]],  Assam. He was popularly known as 'Agnikobi' (\u0985\u0997\u09cd\u09a8\u09bf\u0995\u09ac\u09bf).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sonitpur.gov.in/culture.htm |title=culture |publisher=Sonitpur.gov.in |date= |accessdate=2013-05-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130822073644/http://sonitpur.gov.in/culture.htm |archive-date=22 August 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Politically, he was strongly nationalistic. He opposed the introduction of Bengali as the official language of Assam in 1871. At the annual meeting of the [[Indian National Congress]] in 1886 in [[Calcutta]], he participated as a delegate for Assam. In 1929 he sat as Secretary General of the Organization Culture [[Asam Sahitya Sabha]] ago. He was also the president of the Asam Sahitya Sabha in 1929 held at [[Jorhat district]], Assam.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vedanti.com/News/assam_sahitya_sabha_is_the_forem.htm |title=Asam Sahitya Sabha is the foremost and the most popular organization of Assam |publisher=Vedanti.com |accessdate=2013-05-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130926194342/http://www.vedanti.com/News/assam_sahitya_sabha_is_the_forem.htm |archivedate=2013-09-26 }}</ref> He campaigned for the abolition of the box security regulations and promoted the education of women. He also participated in the swadeshi movement in 1905-06.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=GE2o4QQV7UgC&lpg=PA52&dq=Kamalakanta%20Bhattacharya%20(Assam)&pg=PA52#v=onepage&q=Kamalakanta%20Bhattacharya%20(Assam)&f=false |title=Brahmo Samaj and North-East India - Dipankar Banerjee - Google Books |publisher=Books.google.co.in |date= |accessdate=2013-05-15|isbn=9788179751763 |year=2006 }}</ref>\n\n==Literary works==\n* ''Manat mor para Katha'' (autobiography)\n* ''Chintanala'' (\"The Fire of Thoughts\", a collection of poems, 1870)<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=bMsGmbALl5sC&lpg=PA95&dq=Kamalakanta%20Bhattacharya%20(Assam)&pg=PA78#v=onepage&q=Kamalakanta%20Bhattacharya%20(Assam)&f=false |title=Assamese Literature - S. N. Sharma - Google Books |publisher=Books.google.co.in |date= |accessdate=2013-05-15|isbn=9783447017367 |year=1976 }}</ref>\n* ''Chinta Tarangini'' (\"The Stream of Thought Waves\", a collection of poems, 1933)<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=sqBjpV9OzcsC&lpg=PA196&dq=Kamalakanta%20Bhattacharya%20(Assam)&pg=PA660#v=onepage&q=Kamalakanta%20Bhattacharya%20(Assam)&f=false |title=A History of Indian Literature 1911-1956: Struggle for Freedom: Triumph and ... - Sisir Kumar Das - Google Books |publisher=Books.google.co.in |date= |accessdate=2013-05-15|isbn=9788172017989 |year=1991 }}</ref>\n* ''Ashtabakrar Atmajivani''\n* ''Ashtabakra'' (poetry)\n\n==See also==\n* [[Assamese literature]]\n* [[History of Assamese literature]]\n* [[List of Asam Sahitya Sabha presidents]]\n* [[List of Assamese writers with their pen names]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://creative.sulekha.com/eminent-personalities-of-assam_467977_blog Short biography] at creative.sulekha.com.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070717115154/http://www.sarai.net/fellowships/independent/archival-submissions/fellowships-04-05/uddipan-dutta-the-growth-of-print-nationalism-and-assamese-identity-in-two-early-assamese-magazines/page-8/ Few lines by Kamalakanta Bhattacharya from his article \"Jatiyo Unnoti\"] at sarai.net.\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bhattacharya, Kamalakanta}}\n[[Category:Writers from Assam]]\n[[Category:Asom Sahitya Sabha Presidents]]\n[[Category:1853 births]]\n[[Category:1936 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Sonitpur district]]\n[[Category:Assamese-language poets]]\n[[Category:19th-century Indian poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian poets]]\n[[Category:Indian male essayists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian essayists]]\n[[Category:19th-century Indian essayists]]\n[[Category:19th-century male writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian male writers]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kamalakanta_Bhattacharya_(Assam)"}
{"title_page": "Nepenthes burkei", "text_new": "{{Speciesbox\n|image = Nepenthes_burkei_ASR_062007_mt_halcon_mindoro.jpg\n|image_caption = ''Nepenthes burkei'' lower pitcher.  Mount Halcon, Mindoro.\n|status = LR/cd\n|status_system = IUCN2.3\n|status_ref = <ref>von Arx, B., J. Schlauer & M. Groves 2001. [https://www.kew.org/sites/default/files/CITES_Carnivorous_Plant_Checklist.pdf ''CITES Carnivorous Plant Checklist''.] The Cromwell Press, United Kingdom.</ref>\n|genus = Nepenthes\n|species = burkei\n|authority = Hort.[[Veitch Nurseries|Veitch]] ''ex'' [[Maxwell T. Masters|Mast.]] (1889)<ref name=Masters1889>Masters, M.T. 1889. [https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/25922666 New or noteworthy plants. ''Nepenthes Burkeii''.] ''The Gardeners' Chronicle'', series 3, '''6'''(149): 492\u2013493.</ref>\n|synonyms = *''Nepenthes burkeii''<br><small>Hort.[[Veitch Nurseries|Veitch]] ''ex'' [[Maxwell T. Masters|Mast.]] (1889)<ref name=Masters1889 /></small><br><small>[original spelling]</small>\n}}\n\n'''''Nepenthes burkei''''', named after British [[plant collector]] [[David Burke (botanist)|David Burke]], {{cn|date=September 2019}} is a tropical [[pitcher plant]] native to the island of [[Mindoro]] in the [[Philippines]], where it grows at an elevation of 1100\u20132000&nbsp;m.<ref name=McPherson>McPherson, S.R. 2009. ''[[Pitcher Plants of the Old World]]''. 2 volumes. Redfern Natural History Productions, Poole.</ref> It is very closely related to ''[[Nepenthes sibuyanensis|N.&nbsp;sibuyanensis]]'' and ''[[Nepenthes ventricosa|N.&nbsp;ventricosa]]''. It has only recently entered wider cultivation.\n\n==Infraspecific taxa==\n\nTwo varieties of ''N.&nbsp;burkei'' have been described.\n\n*''Nepenthes burkei'' var. ''excellens'' Hort.[[Veitch Nurseries|Veitch]] ''ex'' Marshall (1890)\n*''Nepenthes burkei'' var. ''prolifica'' Mast. (1890)<ref>Masters, M.T. 1890. [https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/25924768 New or noteworthy plants. ''Nepenthes Burkeii'' Mast. var. ''prolifica''.] ''The Gardeners' Chronicle'', series 3, '''8'''(190): 184.</ref>\n\n==Natural hybrids==\n*''[[Nepenthes alata|N.&nbsp;alata]]'' \u00d7 ''N.&nbsp;burkei''<ref name=McPherson />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{Refbegin|2}}\n* [Anonymous] 1889. [https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/25922560 ''Nepenthes'' at Messrs. Veitch's.] ''The Gardeners' Chronicle'', series 3, '''6'''(145): 388.\n* [Anonymous] 1889. [https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/25922744 ''Nepenthes Burkeii''.] ''The Gardeners' Chronicle'', series 3, '''6'''(151): 566.\n* Bauer, U., C.J. Clemente, T. Renner & W. Federle 2012. Form follows function: morphological diversification and alternative trapping strategies in carnivorous ''Nepenthes'' pitcher plants. ''Journal of Evolutionary Biology'' '''25'''(1): 90\u2013102. {{DOI|10.1111/j.1420-9101.2011.02406.x}}\n* Co, L. & W. Suarez 2012. [http://www.philippineplants.org/Families/Nepenthaceae.html Nepenthaceae]. Co's Digital Flora of the Philippines.\n* {{in lang|fr}} Jarry-Desloges, R. 1903. [https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/8860522 Vari\u00e9t\u00e9s nouvelles ou rares de ''Nepenthes'']. ''Le Jardin'' '''17''': 72.\n* Kurata, S. 1968. Mindoro/North Borneo Expedition. Part 1&2. ''[[The Journal of Insectivorous Plant Society]]'' No. 45.\n* Kurata, S. & M. Toyoshima 1972. Philippine species of ''Nepenthes''. ''The Gardens' Bulletin Singapore'' '''26'''(1): 155\u2013158. [https://web.archive.org/web/20110722151730/http://www.sbg.org.sg/research/publicationbulletin.asp?sRange=1970-1979&sYear=1972 Abstract]\n* Macfarlane, J.M. 1927. The Philippine species of ''Nepenthes''. ''The Philippine Journal of Science'' '''33'''(2): 127\u2013140.\n* McPherson, S.R. & V.B. Amoroso 2011. ''[[Field Guide to the Pitcher Plants of the Philippines]]''. Redfern Natural History Productions, Poole.\n* {{in lang|de}} McPherson, S. & T. Gronemeyer 2008. Die Nepenthesarten der Philippinen: eine Fotodokumentation. ''[[Das Taublatt]]''